review_data.review: Recently went here for a friends birthday as a large group of 12. We had been put into a private room away from the main area - which we were glad about as it was extremely loud in the main restaurant. The cocktails list is poor - most sound fairly unappetising and the only few we tried were not great & we wouldn't have ordered a 2nd. One had an ice cube in which was the size of the glass so was an utter rip off for what you receive. Once at the table, we asked for the wine list which was apparently non-existent as the waitress came back & read 7 wines from her notepad (not being able to tell us anything about any of them)! She explained they were between wine lists, however even if this is the case its fairly poor for any restaurant to not be able to manage this smoothly. We opted for the safe option of Prosecco and beers - after our 2nd bottle of Prosecco, none of the rest of the bottles were cold which the waitress seemed pretty embarrassed about. She also managed to spill half a glass over my friend when pouring it out. The food was ok, we ordered starters to share (the prawns were tasty) and each ordered a main with some vegetables to share too. At the point of mains, you are basically paying for the spectacle only as the portions are fairly small & food is fairly bland & overcooked. I had the seafood special & the salmon was the best thing since its such an oily fish it could take the extra cooking. The lobster was unfortunately a bit chewy. The egg fried rice was also very blend. Each person also got a pair of ramekins with a couple of sauces - these were not nice & didn't compliment the fish at all, one being overly mustardy - assumably to go with steak. For the entainment value, its a bit of fun with a group of friends but I wouldn't go here just for the food. It was also very expensive for what it is - our bill was over £120 per person by the end, which was without desserts & there were a few people driving. I would rather spend that sort of money knowing I'm going to get much better food & service. Unfortunately, we won't be returning and I wouldn't recommend to any food lovers thinking of going.

These guys know to do their job very well and I am sure to repeat the visit soon.

review_data.review: My BF and I reviewed Manzil La Tortue before we arrived in Marrakech, we definitely wanted to try out this place. review_data.review_title: Husband and Wife team serving delicious, flavorful meals
review_data.review: 3 words - MAKE A RESERVATION. It was off-peak season when my husband and I went and we got a reservation through our hotel. Boy am I glad we did because we saw about 10 couples get turned down for not having one. Almost every table was marked "reserved" when we arrived at opening.  There is a good reason for the reservations because the food is so delicious, so flavorful, and home cooked right behind the counter by the husband of the husband/wife team. The wife serves the food and takes the orders and she is SO friendly (unless you dont have a reservation).  They have a good wine selection and the menu is significantly large. I was feeling a little under the weather when we got there so I got a soup - oh my gosh - it was just a simple mushroom soup but we soaked up every last drop with the bread and she came over and hugged us because she saw me soaking up the last bit of liquid and laughed at us. But it was that good. We also got the tomato balls, a must for being in Greece, and they were served with tzatziki, SO GOOD. My husband complimented that for a fried food it was so light. We also got the beer chicken and a seabass - both were amazing, we finished basically everything. They also give a complimentary dessert (assuming they rotate). Ours was some phyllo dough with some cream maybe (not really sure) but so good. The wife also takes a picture of every table and puts it on her facebook site, which I think is pretty cool.  We wanted to go back a second time in our 3 dinners we had in Santorini, but then figured we should try something else....regreted not going back. Absolute must - please go you will not be disappointed.

review_data.review_title: Loved it so much we went back twice
review_data.review: My husband and I ate dinner here our first night in Lisbon. We made a reservation on google, and it was honored. Suggest making a reservation in advance, as it seems pretty popular. Just FYI the restaurant looks like it is in a residential area, depending on where you come from. But it is with a cluster of some other restaurants. Indoor/outdoor dining options.  The pasta is homemade and super fresh, almost as good as when we were in Italy. Great wine/drink list, and reasonable prices for what you get. Good selection of appetizers, and had very friendly service. They offer complimentary limoncello after dinner. The bathrooms were also very clean.  We ended up also having this as our last dinner, since it was so good. Lots of options for both meat eaters, and vegetarians. The appetizers are a very good size, and so were the pasta portions.  My husband had the linguine with prawns the first night, and said it was one of the best he has had. He also said the same about the Amatriciana (wasn't super spicy). I got the ragù the first night, which was excellent, and the macaroni with the asparagus & pancetta the 2nd night, which was super light and full of flavor.

Located on an unassuming picture postcard South Kensington Street, Launceston Place is understated Michelin level cuisine at an affordable price. We had the three course fixed price lunch which came with a glass of fizz but with the option of choosing dishes from the a la Carte menu. The food was a real delight - creative food imaginatively presented and cooked to perfection; coupled with excellent suggestions from the sommelier. Everything was perfect and the service faultless - wonderfully attentive, engaging but not intrusive. This was an amazing dining experience and one we will undoubtedly be repeating - soon.

review_data.review_title: Utterly romantic Italian restaurant in the heart of the medina
review_data.review: This is a stunning and very romantic restaurant housed within a jewel-like riad which is tucked away down a narrow alleyway in the heart of the medina. Tables are situated around a pool and a central marble courtyard with a mosaic clad fountain. A large speaker provides some cool background beats. The restaurant offers two menus – Moroccan and Italian – with the ability to mix and match both. The latter offered a welcome break from the traditional tagines. The king prawns with diced tomatoes and cocktail sauce and the eggplant mozzarella for starters were both beautifully seasoned and bursting with flavour and the home made fettucine and tortellini parmesan cream for main brought back fond memories of some of the best Italian pasta houses. There is an extensive wine list although the Moroccan wine is slightly on the expensive side. The only downside was the service which can best be described as unfriendly and unengaging and we felt a little rushed with courses arriving quickly when we had indicated we would like a break or, in the case of the bill, unprompted. It was slightly odd to be taken to a back room to pay the bill by credit card but I had nothing to fear in that all of the staff were extremely courteous and polite. This was our stand out favourite restaurant during our nine night stay in Marrakesh and we cannot wait to return.  Tip: Ignore the young men waiting to greet you when you leave the restaurant who will seek to persuade you to follow them on a different route back to the main square on the basis that the conventional route is closed at night. This is a standard ruse at this (and many other) locations and an attempt to fleece you of your hard earned dirhams……

review_data.review_title: Not hugely impressed and very expensive
review_data.review: This is a very pretty restaurant on the beachfront at the Anantara hotel. The location and set up is very nice, and having a meal beside the beach with the crashing waves in the background is very romantic and soaking with atmosphere and style.  Service: The service was exemplary as expected at an Anantara. Attentive, helpful, and unobtrusive. They were kind enough to help move us inside to the air conditioned space which helped when it became too hot. They explained much of the dishes to us as well which was nice. When we left they got us a buggy to the reception and called our hotel and asked them to send a buggy to collect us. We were very impressed and pleased with this.  Food: The menu is very limited with only a few options for starters, mains and desserts. I was hoping for more seafood dishes and options. Their hallmark dish was seafood cooked on top of salt bricks. Heating the bricks and cooking it on top allows the seafood to absorb some of the flavour of the exotic salts. It felt gimmicky and I could not really taste any great benefit. I ordered the prawn version and it tasted like regular grilled prawns and was nothing special. I hoped to have some of the famous Thai flavours and passion reflected in the food. But I found the meal a bit bland. Don’t get me wrong, the food was fresh and all was very well executed but the mains were really not that interesting. The salt sommelier was there to assist with different types of salt to enhance your meal. I am a fan of interesting salts but again, this felt a bit forced. I could barely tell the difference between the salts and quite frankly, didn’t care. I just wanted to really good, tasty seafood. The starters were very good – most especially the rocket and pear salad which was quite WOW but a very small portion. The desserts were nicely made but nothing extraordinary. There was also a seafood feast but for the price, did not seem well worth it.  Price: This place was very expensive. I dont normally mind paying for good food but this felt unnecessarily expensive for what it was. I love Ananatra as a hotel and frequently dine at their restaurants even when I am not staying with them but the pricing of the is menu felt much too expensive for the food you were getting. Even if the price were lower, I would not be keen to come back again as I don’t find the food (except the salad) worth the inflated cost. It is a rarity that I do not like an Anantara establishment but the balance of value for money for atmosphere – made me feel disappointed.  I would not go back again for dinner as nothing interested my taste buds. I would not mind to have a drink or light snack there but as a dinner, I felt I could get better food, variety and price at one of the other dining options on the hotel property.

The fish was good enough, but the miso was added as a sauce (vs glazed on top) which was disappointing. The unique black cod taste was lost on the grill and the luscious oiliness of the fish was lost. My son ordered beef and eat everything as it was served medium so soft to eat in bite size pieces so he liked it. I am not a fan of the food and only attended on the request of my son.  Value – teppanyaki is always expensive. My young son and I had 2 mains, 1 starter and a glass of wine and it cost us £90. Every time I pay the bill for a teppanyaki dinner, I vow never to come back and year after year the kids beg to come back for the show which obviously made the meal delicious to them.  Benhihana does the teppanyaki show well and kids and groups will enjoy the experience. It seems fully booked all the time so there is certainly an audience for it. But it is not good value for money, and the food is uninteresting and bland (even with their sauce options). It was such a great find by my boyfriend, who wanted to take me somewhere special for my birthday on January 4th and had booked it from trawling through TripAdvisor, not that he had to trawl far. This little restaurant is so quaint and delightful, it has so much charm, from the place itself to the waitresses and chef who all severed us at one point. A little music (or a tad louder) would have only added to the lovely ambiance. To start we had a gin cocktail as an aperitif whilst we perused over the wine menu. We were then given cured meat, bread and home made butter - this butter was to die for. We selected a bottle of wine (all great prices compared to other restaurants) and soon after our dishes began arriving one by one. I can't actually remember what was in every single one but I do know they were all delicious! The octopus was so tender, the fish lovely and light, the beef was so flavoursome, the little onion thing was amazingly tasty (how did you make an onion taste like that?), the dessert was nice but I would have preferred something a little lighter. I did get a candle in my dessert which was really sweet, my boyfriend couldn't remember mentioning that is was my birthday. We thoroughly enjoyed every last bite. The waitress was so lovely and friendly, we also figured out it was the chef who served us also which we loved. You could see their passion for food when they served us each dish and told us all the components.  I love tasting menus, they are my favourite, especially surprise ones! You are always watching and listening to see what the person opposite you is getting so you know what to expect. This is also amazingly great value for money, at only 49 euros each. Leave about 2-2.5 hours to enjoy the experience. An absolute dream, thank you so much Aspic for the best birthday! We went on to the Moulin Rouge afterwards, which is only 5 minutes away in a taxi.

Re'Tasco is so far away from the city centre that the owner told us that he always worries about no-shows when he gets bookings from tourists.  Well, we showed up, and we had a blast. The steak is incredible - this coming from someone who usually avoids steak (and beef in general), but the starter of cockles in garlicky broth was - if anything - even better.  They were a bit shorts on waiters, but the ones they had were great, and we got good advice on the wine selection too.

We had made a reservation and when we turned up at the restaurant there was a couple just in front of us who had arrived without a reservation. Without asking us first, the guy on the door showed them straight to a table and when he then came back to welcome us, we then had to wait for about 10 minutes while he found a table (clearly he hadn’t checked the reservations before seating the other couple and/or had given our table away).  No apology, pretty inattentive service - having experienced amazing customer service in NYC, this guy definitely wasn’t someone I’d have put in charge of arrivals!  When we were seated, there was barely any room at the tiny tables. The restaurant was very busy so consequently it was incredibly noisy and while I know this contributes to atmosphere, it was impossible to have a quiet conversation (not least because the other tables were so so close!).  Food was good, but honestly I wasn’t blown away - I’ve definitely had better Italian food elsewhere in NYC and in Glasgow and London.  We had the duetto bruschetta to start with burrata, porcini and truffle and guacamole and lobster. It was nice, although the truffle was overpowering and I personally am not particularly convinced by the pairing of guacamole and lobster.  Then we had the Bucantini cacio e pepe with truffle and a special ravioli dish with seafood sauce and mussels.  Cacio e Pepe is my all time favourite Italian dish. I’m afraid I wasn’t blown away by this one. The pasta was a little more than al dente and the truffle sauce overpowered the simple cacio e pepe sauce too much.  The ravioli was filled with spinach and ricotta accompanying a very rich seafood sauce, it was nice but again a little heavy.  We had a very nice bottle of Primitivo, that was probably the highlight.  Generally the service wasn’t great - probably because it was so busy, but still. Twice in the hour we were there birthdays were announced with music so loud it could burst your ear drums - a tradition I don’t mind so much because it’s nice to make a fuss of someone on their bday but the music went on for so long, long after people had lost interest!  I don’t like writing negative reviews because it is so difficult running and maintaining restaurants profitably and so all the positives should be celebrated. This small school is impressively committed to fighting poverty and human trafficking via vocational training. Sala Bai enrolls only the most disfavored Cambodian youths and provides a year long hospitality training (plus housing, food, clothing, health care etc) absolutely free of charge. I lift my hat to this achievement and encourage you to book a lunch! Thank you.

A hospitality old timer, the little Siem Reap Sala Bai Hotel School has captured my heart & soul through its commitment, tuition quality, consistency, humanity and performance. Check their website as SB closes 2-3 months in summer before greeting new students. Returning as often as possible I know them now a bit. The lunch (part of practical training) is always good and of very good value and quality. Choice of well composed Khmer or Western light set menus; I have never been disappointed. review_data.review: We had lunch at this restaurant on Sunday July 6th.  When we had visited this restaurant, several years back, we were pleasantly surprised by the ambiance and quality of food. So when we arrived in NYC this 4th of July weekend, Utsav was the 1st restaurant that came to mind for Indian food. I made a reservation to make sure we had a place.  We arrived with a lot of anticipation, but were utterly disappointed, by the time we left.  The restaurant started us of on the wrong foot, by stacking up unclean plates. Every plate we picked up (from the stack of plates provided) had food particles stuck to the bottom. Either their dishwasher was spoilt, or whoever was washing the dishes, did a shoddy job. I had to pick through at least 10 plates (supposedly clean) before getting hold of a “somewhat clean plate”.  At the Appetizer counter, there was a man preparing chat. I asked him for a helping, and was told that they will bring it to our table. By the time we left, no one had bothered to get us the chat.  The food quality was well below average, and not commensurate of a restaurant charging over $20/person for the buffet. There were very few items, both for the vegetarian and the non-vegetarian palate. The food tasted like “production line” preparation. There were two desert dishes that were clearly below par.  I would not recommend this restaurant to anyone looking for good Indian food. Utsav has clearly lost its edge.

Large portions, meat tough. Salad large enough to share with two people. Grilled provolone cheese was excellent. Best part was the penquin of cinzano! Service good. Portion size large, under order, you can always order more but if you order too much it is overwhelming.

review_data.review_title: Our Best Meal in Paris, Ever
review_data.review: The whole night was made magical by the owner, service, food, and setting. Been to Paris a number of times. Never had a single meal that was spot on in every way. Walked in about 20 minutes early and the owner immediately knew our reservation. He seated the 4 of us at an odd table right up in front of the bar. We were unsure, but as the evening unfolded we learned this was exactly the spot to have. He could watch over us from the bar like a wonderful host. We also learned he custom made the table which worked out exceptionally well. He made the wine suggestions which were spot on. Every course was wonderful. I have never taken photos of my food, but there is first time for everything. We left feeling we were leaving someones home. A night to remember and he and the staff were gracious to our limited French, we even shared laughs about how bad we were in the language department.

review_data.review: I’m more sceptical of reviews recently, but this place had such great reviews that seemed genuine, so we thought we’d try it. We booked via WhatsApp (which their website details) only an hour before they were opening and got a very quick response. I’ll get my only slight criticism out of the way! It’s a little bit cramped, but it’s so popular I can’t blame them for accommodating as many people as possible. We weren’t keen on the high seats at barrel tables that we were initially allocated, but there was no problem at all in offering us alternative seating at a table. So, onto the food! It’s simply exceptional. The ordering process is such a great idea, with you ticking the boxes next to your choices. We had 5 veggie & vegan dishes that were absolutely superb. In fact the beet hummus with chicory dressed with fig balsamic was one of the best things I’ve ever eaten! My husband and son also had a fish dish and desserts, which they said were equally outstanding. Finally, we couldn’t believe how hard the 2 owners worked. Nothing was too much trouble, and they clearly love what they do. Highly recommended without hesitation.

Had dinner with my family and we were pleased with the taste, prices, and service. The place itself is not that attractive, however the food will make you get beyond this. The only downside would be that the mains and appetizers were brought at once to our table, no idea why.

Faraona ripiena, delicious, crispy on the surface with a melting filling. I believe that the quality of the dishes shows the competence and love of Theo Randall for the raw materials, the ingredients and the care and passion he puts into the preparations together with his excellent team. The dessert, ricotta cheesecake, was also very good, with a welcome addition of good wishes for me. Excellent wine list from which we chose a Nebbiolo delle Langhe by Ascheri 2019, very good. I had a perfect evening from all points of view. Thanks to Theo and his team!

There was a queue developing outside so I get that they needed our table back but it would’ve been nice not to have to rush our final drinks.

review_data.review_title: Excellent Meal, Excellent Service, Perfect Evening
review_data.review: We came here for dinner on the night we landed in Paris. Our flight was supposed to arrive at 8:20pm, and their last order was at 10:15pm (be aware that even though they offer 10:30pm reservations on La Fourchette, they don't actually do that), so I initially canceled because I was worried we'd miss the reservation. They were exceedingly nice and understanding during the email exchange, and so when we arrived on time and realized we could still make it, we had our hotel call them, and they were able to accommodate us.  Particularly for a late night dinner, the meal was better than I could have expected. The servers were kind and didn't rush us at all even though we ordered the chef's menu. Particularly memorable was the artichoke soup which was divine, the best I'd ever had with bits of artichoke mixed in with the velvety smooth soup. My husband, who is usually a non-meat eater, said the lamb was one of the best he had tasted. If you come here, you must have the bread, even if you are trying to cut down on carbs. It's absolutely delicious. On this night, we had something that looked like parker rolls, but actually tasted like a nice focaccia, and a perfectly baked sourdough slice.  If you are a dessert lover like me, you will love the long list of some of the most scrumptious choices I've seen at a restaurant in a long time. The menu came with a caramel mille-feuille, which I enjoyed, but I also saw tantalizing plates of soufflés, berry tarts etc etc making its way toward other tables. I would love to come and just eat all of their desserts.  The restaurant was located inside the Bristol hotel, which is a former palace. The warm and unpretentious service combined with the amazing food even made me curious about staying here next time.  Pricewise, this is a one Michelin restaurant, so it's in the typical range of similarly rated establishments. Frankly, however, this was a better meal than two-Michelin places we've been to on out previous trip two months ago, so from that perspective we considered it to be, maybe not a bargain, but completely worth it.

review_data.review_title: Good Service, But Very Limited Choices and High Prices
review_data.review: Good- but overrated… We looked forward to our dinner at Pur , but were disappointed in the menu. There were only four entrées to choose from and one was a cheese platter. The other entrée choices were sea bass , wyagu beef and sweet breads. My husband wanted none of them however he chose the wyagu beef. The sauce for the beef was excellent and he enjoyed it however at €135 it should be more than very good . I ordered the Seabass and found it adequate. The risotto with curry that came with the beef also had an excellent sauce. Some of the servers, including James and Amin, were very good. Leopold never brought the citrus vinaigrette I requested and seemed to completely forget it. He also had to be asked to serve us bread. There were many “extras” that were provided at no charge,but being very gourmet,required a receptive palate. I loved the artichoke appetizer bite with curry,but my husband didn’t care for any of them. We ordered a la carte,but with a €90 bottle of wine ( which was the least expensive Bordeaux on the menu) and coffee, our bill before tip was €333. We are world travelers and have stayed at some of the best hotels. Overall, I would give the food a B-. My husband gave it a much lower rating than that. If we had ordered the six course fixed menu with wine, the bill would have been well over €600. You would have had the same four entrees as well. Interesting experience, but we would never go back.

Fantastic food - from starters through to dessert, delicious drinks (Negroni) and fantastic service. We were served by Agus and he was extremely attentive from the moment we arrived. Recommend checking Chope for vouchers, we got 29% off our bill, no strings attached.

Small restaurant just off the main strip and did not disappoint. The chicken sate was genuinely one of the best things I’ve ever eaten. review_data.review_title: Great food, beautiful ambiance, exceptional service
review_data.review: We only stayed at La Siesta Trendy for two nights and on the first night in Vietnam we had to have the obligatory street food which was great. For the second night, and after a very long day of touring the city, we decided to have dinner at The Red Bean. Greeted by friendly staff at the lift door, we were ushered to an intimate table and offered a menu with a great selection of dishes and drinks including cocktails. For cocktails we had: The Naked Man Pina Colada Both very moorish, so we had seconds at the end of our meal! We would recommend the spring rolls platter which had two fresh rolls, two crispy seafood rolls and two crispy Hanoi pork rolls. This was followed by a beautifully presented steaming bowl of pho. The pho at the restaurant was a delicately flavoured broth with rice noodles and tender beef. It was different to the rustic flavours you’d get from street food vendors and equally as wonderful. Every pho recipe has some hidden secrets and this was evident in the subtlety different flavours. Mango sticky rice wrapped up the evening and the warm coconut flavoured rice with sweet mango was everything that I was expecting and looking forward to trying for the first time. It was a great restaurant choice for our last night in Hanoi and if we are ever here again we will definitely visit.

We arrived in happy hour and had a few drinks before ordering food. The menu was very good and I opted for prawns. Very good. We were going to stay longer but the music was turned too loud for us. review_data.review: While visiting Istanbul, my wife and myself read reviews about this particular restaurant..  And have to say, we absolutely loved our culinary experience here.. But if you want an authentic ambience, great welcome and really genuine Turkish food, then you'll enjoy eating here...  Not easy to find as it's slightly off the main area of tourist haunts..  One app that will help guide you through the streets to find this restaurant, put MAPS.ME on your phone...  No Internet requirement, as it uses GPS signal..  From Hagia Sofia Square, follow up the hill where the Trams go, find Burger King.. Turn left so BK is on your right... Follow this road down to a junction in the road.. The old Cistern is on left of junction..  There's a small road sharp right, don't take that road.. Take next right.. Follow down, to fork in road.. Keep left, keep walking and Restaurant comes up on your right...

review_data.review_title: Best Indian Food in Siem Reap
review_data.review: Mr. Narain is a wonderful host. Vastly experienced in the hospitality business, his restaurant is easily the best in Cambodia for Indian food. A great eclectic menu to satisfy all tastes, I seriously recommend this restaurant to anyone who likes quality with a great ambience.
I had a delicious vegetarian moussaka which came with pita and tzatziki. My partner had seafood pasta made with macaroni. Both were excellent as was the service.

For a family of five, cooking breakfasts for five days can be daunting. So it's out of necessity and convenience that we had our daily buffet breakfast in this restaurant. And we are very happy we did. Food offers and spreads are great.For starters, they had so many appetisers and soups including their culinary masterpiece and favourite Tom Yang. This time it's on the light side version as against the heavy soup that is typically served. Great variety of Japanese and international cuisine : bacon, sausages, ham, omelletes,sushi bar, salad bar, desserts: local fruits like dragon fruit, pineapple,jackfruit, etc. A great way to start the day of beautiful memories. Of course, one can also order a la carte for set breakfast menus which in itself is very generous in serving size. Be early coz waiting time can be challenging.

The menu did not indicate many vegetarian dishes, but I asked for Pad Thai without meat and it was made with tofu and extra vegetables and was very good. I didn't particularly like the selection of starters. The vegetarian starter included fried spring rolls, which are unusual in a Thai restaurant (they usually have the type with rice paper that are not fried), and deep fried, battered vegetables, which in my view defeat the purpose of eating vegetables. I did not order wine, but my friends did not care for the wine selections--surprising since it is not difficult to find good wine in New Zealand. review_data.review: Over the years I’ve come to expect Mlýnec to deliver a very good festival menu, which is why this restaurant was the fourth and last round with my Danish friends before they headed back home. It is safe to say that the restaurant didn’t disappoint. We were all blown away by the experience. We were greeted by the manager (I believe) and sat down at a nice table. The interior of the restaurant has been redone, and we liked it. Particularly we liked the acoustics of the room. Noise doesn’t travel from table to table, and we could have a relaxed conversation without raising our voices or listening in on whatever was being discussed by the table next to ours. We had a bowl of bread with 3 different kinds of fresh and slightly warm bread. It was accompanied by a herb spread which had nice, subtle flavours and a perfect temperature. I wanted more bread! But thank God they didn’t give me any (I didn't ask for it), because we were all completely full, when we left the restaurant a couple of hours later. The amuse bouche was delicate foam of smoked potatoes. There were some crunchy bits on top and a bit of sour notes from tiny pieces of pickled vegetables as well. These 2 elements gave some texture, and it was a brilliant little dish. The starter was smoked char with almond milk “caviar”, beluga lentils, horseradish, and marjoram. The trout had a firm, yet tender texture and had received just the right amount of smoke. The subtle horseradish sauce with marjoram complimented both fish and lentils very well and made everything come together. The lentils were perfectly cooked – I am not sure if “al dente” is a way to describe lentils, but I’ll risk it. The almond milk caviar was mainly on the plate for texture, I believe – it didn’t pack a lot of flavour. I like that the “eggs” had different sizes. That worked well visually and also when it came to the texture. The size of the portion was generous – we all agreed that it wouldn’t have been strange at all, if they had served one piece of trout instead of the two nice portions on our plates. The main dish was veal rib eye, beans, dried beef, beets, cashews, and demi glace. We were given a choice how we would like our meat prepared, and we all chose medium. Mine was closer to medium rare, and that was perfectly fine with me. The first impression of the dish came from tasting the demi glace, which was one of the best I’ve ever had. Only the master of sauces, Steven Trumpfheller, has served me a better one. So rich and full of flavour and reduced to the point where it would make my lips stick together. The steak was tender and well seasoned, and it hade more and deeper flavour than I would have expected from veal – more like a young bull. There were 3 different types of beans on the side, all cooked to perfection. The beets added an earthy and sweet/sour dimension, and the small bites of smoked and dried beef held it together, although my first bite was very tough (the rest weren’t). Just as it was the case with the starter, everything on the plate created a perfect combination, and the dish was quite filling. I regretted not having saved a slice of bread to wipe my plate clean with. Not to embarrass my two friends at the table I decided not to lick the sauce off my plate, but the thought crossed my mind. The dessert was macaroon in two ways, cherry, chocolate, tangerine, and basil garnished with raspberries and a blackberry. The macaroon on the side was good, but to me the star of the dish was the clever composition in the middle. I tried tasting the different elements individually, and they went almost all the way around the palate, except for saltiness. Sweet, sour, tart, bitter. And then when they all met in combination with the chewy and a little bit gooey macaroon bottom, it was simply a heavenly mouthful. The menu mentions a pre-dessert as a palate cleanser. Previously it has been a ball of sorbet. They forgot to serve it at our table, but they found out and insisted that we had coffee on the house, accompanied with cute cubes of chocolaty caramel. It was a nice finish to our meal. The service was friendly and attentive, and we were given plenty of time between dishes, which we really appreciate. We were served by different waiters, but the manager always kept an eye on our table and checked every once in a while if we were happy – and it was a pleasure chatting with him. Hospitality must lie in his genes. We agreed that this final festival experience was a perfect ending to this year’s adventure as a group – and most definitely we’re looking forward to repeating it next year! There are 2 seats left for the Restaurant festival at Mlýnec this year: 1 seat on the 12/2 at 17:30 and 1 on the 16/2 at 17:30. Grab them!

review_data.review: I've been curious for a long time how good the brunch at Mlýnec is? It's served on Saturdays and Sundays between 11:30-15:00. The menu changes from week to week. The price is Czk. 1.290, - per person. It includes prosecco, red wine, white wine, beer, coffee, freshly squeezed orange juice and other soft drinks ad libitum. My boss, who is pretty awesome - and has asked me out several times this week - is in Prague with her husband, and I thought it appropriate to ask them out, just once. We usually attend the Grand Restaurant Festival together, but that’s not an option this year. Instead we’ve designed our own culinary week. The menu we had yesterday is below. Food is served at the table. We were given dishes to share, and we were pleased with the portion sizes, which allowed us to taste everything. By the time we had done that, we were also absolutely stuffed. Everything we were served was impressively delicious. The praise came in a stream from all three of us. We were impressed with the quality of the prosecco and wines included in what was effectively an all-you-can-drink package. The service was also absolutely perfect. The team of waiters were quite young and they were well trained in the profession, they were polite, friendly, helpful and had both humour and the courage to bring their personalities to work. When we arrived at 11:30, we discussed whether we could have arrived a little later and still had plenty of time before 15:00. But the service was kind enough to give us plenty of time between courses, we had a good time - and by 14:35 we were ready for dessert, which by the way was a feast of flavours and textures and one of the many highlights of the brunch. We'll be back!
